dle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Berkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Barclay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."]},{"name":"Berkley","meanings":["English: variant of   Berkeley  . Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): assimilated form of   Berkowitz  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":4,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":29,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":42,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":51,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Berkeley was born in 1286, in Winterbourne, Berkshire, England. She married John Fitz Stephens II in 1312, in Winterbourne, Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1374, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 88."},"et":{"1286–1374":"1286–1374","1282–1374":"1282–1374","–Male":"Surnud","1314–1386":"1314–1386","1286":"1286","1374":"1374","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1312":"1312","about 1314":"umbes 1314","1453":"1453","1386":"1386","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Winterbourne, Berkshire, England":"Winterbourne, Berkshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Winterbourne, Gloucestershire, England":"Winterbourne, Gloucestershire, England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1286–1374":"1286–1374","1282–1374":"1282–1374","–Male":"Kuollut","1314–1386":"1314–1386","1286":"1286","1374":"1374","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1312":"1312","about 1314":"noin 1314","1453":"145